The dataset is "Sea Ice Concentrations from Nimbus-7 SMMR and DMSP SSM/I-SSMIS Passive Microwave Data" from the National Snow and Ice Data Center (http://nsidc.org/data/nsidc-0051). The grid size is 25x25 km. For testing, we pick one dataset of December 31, 2012.

outdir = "/Volumes/SCIENCE/Ice/RESULTS_BY_AREA/"

testpath = os.path.join(datadir, testfn)

As the file name encodes the date, we can recover the date the data was acquired.

In [5]: 
def fn2date(filepath):
    head, tail = os.path.split(filepath)
    dt = datetime.datetime.strptime(tail[3:11], '%Y%m%d').date()
    return datetime.datetime.strftime(dt, "%Y-%m-%d")

Get data¶

A variable to access the test dataset.

In [9]: 
nsdic = raster.GeoTIFF(testpath)

The scene has 448 by 304 pixels.

In [10]: 
nsdic.nrow, nsdic.ncol
Out[10]:
(448, 304)

As explained in the documentation (http://nsidc.org/data/docs/daac/nsidc0051_gsfc_seaice.gd.html#data_description), the data are 8-bit unsigned integers with allowed values between 0 and 255:

  • The values 0 to 250 are scaled integers represent the average sea ice concentration in the pixel (divide by 2.5 to get percentages).
  • The values 251 to 255 are flags indicating pixels affected by conditions such as the circular mask around the poles, the continental land mass, the coast line, or missing data.

We'll separate the data set up into two to make it easier to plot and associate color schemes with these.

In [11]: 
icedat = np.empty_like(nsdic.data)
icedat[:] = nsdic.data/2.5
icedat[icedat > 250] = 255
maskdat = np.empty_like(nsdic.data)
maskdat = np.ma.MaskedArray(nsdic.data, mask=nsdic.data <= 250)

Geo-stuff: plot overview of the data globally¶

The data come in polar stereographic projection on the WGS 84 datum and spheroid. The central meridian is 45 degrees West (that is, this is the direction pointing downwards on the map).

Plot Pribiloff Island area¶

The latitude and longitude of St George and St Paul Islands.

The coordtransform attribute is a function that transforms between (lon, lat) pairs and (easting, northing) pairs in the projectected coordinate system.

In [20]: 
geog2stereo = nsdic.coordtrans

We can use it to get the coordinates of the islands in the native polar stereographic projection.

In [21]: 
x_pribStG, y_pribStG = geog2stereo(lon_pribStG, lat_pribStG)
x_pribStP, y_pribStP = geog2stereo(lon_pribStP, lat_pribStP)
print(x_pribStG, y_pribStG)

-3064345.37522 2112634.92523

The i, j coordinates of the islands can be calculated directly. However, pygaarst offers a method on the GeoTIFF object with the argument precise=True, which returns the values as floating point.

In [27]:

i_pribStP, j_pribStP = nsdic.xy2ij(x_pribStP, y_pribStP, precise=True)

Zooming in on a map, with rectangle marked.

In [101]: 
width = rectangle.get_width()
height = rectangle.get_height()
orig = rectangle.get_xy()

def rectanglepath(topleftij, width, height):
    ii, jj = topleftij

    a1 = [(i, jj) for i in range(ii, ii+width+1)]
    a2 = [(ii+width, j) for j in range(jj+1, jj+height+1)]
    a3 = [(i, jj+height) for i in range(ii+width-1, ii-1, -1)]
    a4 = [(ii, j) for j in range(jj+height, jj-1, -1)]

    return a1 + a2 + a3 + a4

iijj = rectanglepath((orig[1], orig[0]), height, width)
xxyy = [nsdic.ij2xy(ii, jj) for (ii, jj) in iijj]
lonlat = [nsdic.coordtrans(x, y, inverse=True)  for (x, y) in xxyy]

Ice indices¶

Calculating ice indices for months November, December, January, February, March, April, May. For data before the 1987/1988 winter, we have sea ice coverage every second day. After that, every day, during these months. Sea ice is zero at the Pribilofs during the summer.

How should we quantify the sea ice cover? We can either average the sea ice cover percentages, for example over a month, either along the straight line between the islands or within the rectangle. Or we can count days during which sea ice cover is non-zero (or above a threshold) and sum them up during a November-May season.

Below I calculate and plot the following indices:

  • monthly averages for sea ice cover percentage (pixels directly between islands)
  • monthly averages for sea ice cover percentage (pixels in 3x4 rectangle)
  • number of days during a winter season where all pixels on the straight line between the islands are ice-covered
  • number of days where any pixels on the straight line between the islands are ice-covered

How to loop through months.

In [87]: 
years = range(1978, 2013)
months = range(1, 6) + [11, 12]
allmonths = [(year, month) for year in years for month in months if (year, month ) > (1978, 5)]

BYMONTH = False

pattern_daily = "nt_[1-2][0-9][0-9][0-9][0-9][0-9][0-9][0-9]_*_n.bin.reproj.tif"
pattern_monthly = "nt_[1-2][0-9][0-9][0-9][0-9][0-9]_*_n.bin.reproj.tif"
pattern_slot_monthly = "nt_%s_*_n.bin.reproj.tif"
pattern_slot_daily = "nt_%s[0-9][0-9]_*_n.bin.reproj.tif"
rectangle = Rectangle((31, 148), width=4, height=3, fill=False, ec='khaki')

iceidx1 = []
iceidx2 = []
iceidx3 = []
iceidx4 = []

for yy, mm in allmonths:
    ym = str(yy) + str(mm).zfill(2)
    icesum1 = 0
    icesum2 = 0
    icesum3 = 0
    icesum4 = 0
    print(ym, '... ', end="")
    if BYMONTH:
        monthfiles = glob.glob(os.path.join(datadir, pattern_slot_monthly % ym))
        if len(monthfiles) != 1:
            print("WARNING: unexpected number of files for %s. Should be 1. Found %s." % (ym, len(monthfiles)))
        filenum = 1
    else:
        monthfiles = glob.glob(os.path.join(datadir, pattern_slot_daily % ym))
        filenum = len(monthfiles)
    for datafile in monthfiles:    
        head, tail = os.path.split(datafile)
        dataset = raster.GeoTIFF(datafile)
        icedat = dataset.data/2.5
        icedat[icedat > 250] = 255
        avg_ice1 = np.sum(np.array(icedat[149, 31:35]))/4
        icesum1 += avg_ice1
        avg_ice2 = np.sum(np.array(icedat[148:151, 31:35]))/12
        icesum2 += avg_ice2
        if np.all(np.array(icedat[149, 31:35]) != 0): icesum3 += 1
        if np.any(np.array(icedat[149, 31:35]) != 0): icesum4 += 1
    iceidx1.append(icesum1/filenum)
    iceidx2.append(icesum2/filenum)
    iceidx3.append(icesum3)
    iceidx4.append(icesum4)

Indices 3 and 4 need to be aggregated by year before plotting.

In [97]: 
iceidx31 = {}
iceidx41 = {}

def add_grouped(dic, key, item):
    try:
        dic[key] += item
    except KeyError:
        dic[key] = item
    return dic

for idx, yymm in enumerate(allmonths):
    if yymm[1] <= 6:
        iceidx31 = add_grouped(iceidx31, yymm[0], iceidx3[idx])
        iceidx41 = add_grouped(iceidx41, yymm[0], iceidx4[idx])
    else:
        iceidx31 = add_grouped(iceidx31, yymm[0]+1, iceidx3[idx])
        iceidx41 = add_grouped(iceidx41, yymm[0]+1, iceidx4[idx])
